# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1893-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1892 Cleveland Spiders**, led by star pitcher Cy Young, finished with a 93–56 overall record, second-best in the National League.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] In the first split season in Major League Baseball history, the Spiders finished in fifth place during the first half of the season, and in first place during the second half.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season, they played against the first-half champions, the Boston Beaneaters, in the "World's Championship Series", which the Spiders lost, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The **1892 World Series** followed the first split season in National League history, with the first-half champion Boston Beaneaters (102–48) playing the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders (93–56) in a best-of-nine postseason series to determine the overall champion of the 1892 baseball season.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After the first game ended in a 0–0 tie due to darkness, Boston won the next five games to win the championship.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Contemporary newspaper reports referred to the games as the "**World's Championship Series**" or "**World's Series**".
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] This was the last of the pre-modern-era World Series, and followed similar annual postseason competitions held from 1884 to 1890 between the champions of the National League and the American Association (which collapsed after the 1891 season).
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Later, the Temple Cup would be awarded to the winner of an annual postseason series between National League teams, from 1894 to 1897.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Boston manager Frank Selee worried that late-October weather conditions would lead to postponements and low attendance.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Bookies had the Spiders as the favorite, due to their pitching staff.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Cy Young had gone 36–12 in 49 starts, with a 1.93 earned-run average.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Meanwhile, Boston star Mike "King" Kelly had a batting average of only .189 for the year, and was described as "one of the biggest failures of the base ball season".
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Hugh Duffy of Boston batted .462 with nine runs batted in and six extra-base hits including a home run.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Had the series required more than six games to complete, the remaining games would have been played in New York City.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The first game, which had started at three o'clock, had gone 11 scoreless innings when it was stopped at five o'clock due to darkness.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After a travel day for the teams, the series moved to Boston with the Beaneaters leading, two games to none.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] John Clarkson started for Cleveland in place of Cy Young, who complained of a "lame arm".
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] After an off-day (professional baseball games were not allowed on Sundays in Boston until 1929) the Beaneaters won their fifth game of the series to capture the championship.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The 13 players on their roster split $1000 prize money.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The National League abolished the split season format for 1893, and did not play another split season until 1981, which was caused by a players' strike.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] John Clarkson had started the season with the Beaneaters, and signed with the Spiders after being released at the end of June.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Pitcher Lee Viau also played for both Boston and Cleveland during 1892.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The Beaneaters were later known as the Doves (1907–1910) and the Rustlers (1911) before adopting the nickname of "Braves" in 1912.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The franchise relocated to Milwaukee in 1953, and then moved to Atlanta in 1966, where they remain members of the National League as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] The Spiders' final season was 1899, when they compiled a record of 20–134 (establishing a longstanding record for the worst major league season) after ownership moved their best players to the St.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-world-series] Louis Cardinals, and were one of four teams contracted out of the National League when the league reduced its size to eight teams prior to the 1900 season.
[src:1893-cleveland-spiders-season/1893-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1893 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 73–55 record and a third-place finish in the National League.
